(43, 11, 34, 43, 20, 2, 2, 'where have ye laid him?', 'Connection of Burial and Discovery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking the body of Jesus. In John 11:34, the question ''Where have ye laid him?'' parallels the inquiry in John 20:2 about where Jesus has been laid after his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 35, 42, 19, 41, 41, 'Jesus wept.', 'Connection of Jesus'' Weeping', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' emotional response to loss and sorrow. In John 11:35, Jesus weeps for Lazarus, while in Luke 19:41, he weeps over Jerusalem, highlighting his compassion.', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 35, 58, 4, 15, 15, 'Jesus wept.', 'Empathy in Suffering', 'This connection highlights the emotional depth of Jesus, as seen in ''Jesus wept,'' and His ability to empathize with human suffering in ''touched with the feeling of our infirmities.'' Both passages emphasize Jesus'' shared experience of human emotions and struggles.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 35, 43, 11, 33, 33, 'Jesus wept.', 'Emotional Response of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' deep emotional response to the mourning around him. In John 11:33, he is described as ''groaned in the spirit, and was troubled,'' which sets the stage for his subsequent weeping in John 11:35.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 35, 23, 53, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Grief and Sorrow', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sorrow and grief. In John 11:35, ''Jesus wept'' reflects his deep emotional response, while Isaiah 53:3 describes a man of sorrows, highlighting the shared experience of suffering.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 35, 19, 119, 136, 136, NULL, 'Emotional Responses to Suffering', 'This connection highlights the emotional depth of both passages, as both Jesus and the psalmist express profound sorrow over the consequences of sin and disobedience. The phrase ''run down mine eyes'' in Psalms parallels the deep grief of ''Jesus wept,'' emphasizing a shared lament for human suffering.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 35, 24, 13, 17, 17, 'Jesus wept.', 'Connection of Weeping in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the act of weeping in response to sorrow and loss. Jesus wept over the death of Lazarus, while Jeremiah expresses deep sorrow for the fate of the Lord''s flock.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 35, 18, 30, 25, 25, 'wept', 'Connection of Grief and Compassion', 'This connection highlights the theme of compassion in both passages. In John 11:35, ''Jesus wept'' reflects deep sorrow, while Job 30:25 expresses grief for those in trouble, emphasizing empathy for the suffering.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 36, 43, 11, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Love in John', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of love, as seen in the phrases ''he whom thou lovest'' and ''how he loved him.'' This connection highlights the deep affection Jesus has for Lazarus, which is central to the narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 36, 62, 3, 1, 1, 'Behold how he loved him!', 'Connection of Divine Love', 'This connection highlights the theme of love, as both passages express profound affection. In John 11:36, the Jews observe Jesus'' love, while 1 John 3:1 emphasizes the Father''s love for believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 36, 62, 4, 9, 10, 'how he loved him', 'Connection of Divine Love', 'This connection highlights the theme of love expressed in both passages. In John 11:36, the Jews recognize Jesus'' love, while 1 John 4:9-10 emphasizes God''s love through the sending of His Son.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 36, 66, 1, 5, 5, 'how he loved him', 'Connection of Love in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of love expressed in both passages. In John 11:36, the Jews remark on Jesus'' love, while Revelation 1:5 emphasizes His love for humanity through His sacrificial act.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 36, 43, 14, 21, 23, 'how he loved him', 'Connection of Love in John', 'This connection highlights the theme of love in both passages. In John 11:36, the Jews recognize Jesus'' love, while in John 14:21-23, Jesus explains that love for Him is demonstrated through obedience to His commandments.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 36, 47, 8, 8, 9, 'how he loved him', 'Love and Sacrifice Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of love expressed through sacrifice. In John 11:36, the love of Jesus is evident, while 2 Corinthians 8:8-9 emphasizes His sacrificial love that leads to the enrichment of others.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 36, 49, 5, 25, 25, 'how he loved him', 'Love as a Central Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of love present in both passages. In John 11:36, the expression of love is evident in Jesus'' relationship with Lazarus, while Ephesians 5:25 emphasizes Christ''s love for the church, illustrating the depth and sacrificial nature of love.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 37, 43, 9, 6, 7, 'opened the eyes of the blind', 'Healing and Doubt Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing, as both passages involve a miraculous act by Jesus. In John 11:37, the crowd questions why Jesus did not prevent death, referencing his previous miracle of restoring sight in John 9:6-7.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 37, 19, 78, 19, 20, NULL, 'Questioning God''s Power', 'This connection highlights the questioning of God''s ability to intervene in dire situations. Both passages express doubt about God''s capacity to provide help or sustenance when faced with adversity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 37, 40, 27, 40, 42, NULL, 'Connection of Skepticism and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the skepticism surrounding Jesus'' ability to save. In John, the question arises about his power to prevent death, while in Matthew, the mocking challenges his ability to save himself despite saving others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 37, 41, 15, 32, 32, 'this man should not have died', 'Miraculous Power and Skepticism', 'This connection highlights the skepticism surrounding Jesus'' ability to perform miracles. In both passages, the questioning of Jesus'' power is evident, as people doubt His ability to save or act despite previous miracles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 37, 42, 23, 35, 35, NULL, 'Challenge to Jesus'' Power', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge to Jesus'' ability to save. In John, the crowd questions why Jesus did not prevent death, while in Luke, the rulers mock him for not saving himself despite saving others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 37, 43, 11, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Mourning and Hope', 'Both passages emphasize the belief that Jesus could have prevented Lazarus''s death. Martha expresses her hope that if Jesus had been present, her brother would not have died, while others question why He did not act to save him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 38, 43, 11, 33, 33, 'groaning in himself', 'Emotional Response of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' emotional response to grief. In John 11:33, he ''groaned in the spirit,'' and in John 11:38, he is described as ''groaning in himself'' as he approaches the grave.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 38, 1, 23, 19, 19, 'a cave', 'Connection of Burial and Cave', 'This connection highlights the significance of caves as burial sites in both passages. In John 11:38, Jesus approaches a grave that is described as a cave, paralleling the burial of Sarah in the cave of Machpelah in Genesis 23:19.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 38, 40, 27, 60, 60, 'a stone lay upon it', 'Connection of Tomb and Stone', 'Both passages emphasize a cave or tomb and a stone. In John, Jesus approaches a grave with a stone, while in Matthew, a stone is rolled to the door of a sepulchre. This connection highlights the significance of the stone in relation to burial.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 38, 42, 24, 2, 2, 'a stone lay upon it', 'Connection of Stones in Burial', 'This connection highlights the significance of the stone in both passages. In John 11:38, the stone is present at Lazarus'' grave, while in Luke 24:2, the stone is rolled away from Jesus'' sepulchre, symbolizing a transition from death to life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 38, 23, 22, 16, 16, 'grave', 'Connection of Burial Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a sepulchre, highlighting the act of hewing out a grave in rock. This connection illustrates the significance of burial places in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 38, 43, 20, 1, 1, 'a stone lay upon it', 'Connection of the Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a stone at a grave. In John 11:38, the stone is mentioned as lying upon the cave, while in John 20:1, the stone is noted as taken away from the sepulchre.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 38, 1, 49, 29, 31, 'a cave', 'Burial in a Cave', 'This connection highlights the significance of caves as burial sites in both passages. John 11:38 describes Jesus approaching a grave that is a cave, paralleling Genesis 49:29-31, where burial in a cave is emphasized as a familial tradition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 39, 43, 11, 17, 17, 'he hath been dead four days', 'Connection of Lazarus'' Death', 'Both passages emphasize that Lazarus had been dead for four days, highlighting the severity of his condition before Jesus intervened. This connection underscores the miraculous nature of his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 39, 19, 49, 7, 7, 'he hath been dead four days', 'Redemption and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of death and the inability to redeem oneself or others from it. In John 11:39, Martha acknowledges the finality of death, while Psalms 49:7 emphasizes that no one can redeem another from death.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
